<div class="section-title">
  <h2><span>Project Goals</span></h2>
</div>

<div class="row">
  <div class="col-sm-offset-1 col-sm-10">
    <p>My team and I developed an interactive prototype as part of a Data Visualization class (HCDE 511) at the University of Washington. Very interested in entrepreneurship, we wanted to better understand the startup landscape. We also figured out that such a tool could be valuable to anyone working in startups. We built StartupViz to:</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
  <div class="col-sm-offset-1 col-sm-5">
    <h3>Explore Trends</h3>
    <p>Show overall trends and general information on startups (e.g. which cities have the highest number of startups, which market has received the most funding, which markets are growing and which are shrinking, how cities compare in terms of funding rounds, etc.).</p>
  </div>
  <div class="col-sm-5">
    <h3>Help in Decision Making</h3>
    <p>Show detailed information for those looking to become a part of a startup (e.g. which markets are dominant in which cities, the startup growth rate in a particular city, etc.), and information on investors for those who are a part of a startup and are looking for funding (e.g. which startups and markets investors have funded, during which round they contributed, etc.).</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-title">
  <h2><span>The Data Set</span></h2>
  <p>Removing noise</p>
</div>

<div class="centered-column">
  <h3 class="no-margin-top">CrunchBase</h3>
  <p>The best data set we could find was CrunchBase. CrunchBase allows users to look up any startup or any person related to a startup. It also lists all the events (e.g. funding rounds) that are relevant for specific startups. In total, it contains more than 650k profiles about companies, investors, people, acquisitions, and more. </p>

  <h3>Data Cleaning</h3>
  <p>CrunchBase’s information is provided and maintained by its users. While it contains a lot of detailed information about current tech startups in the US, a large amount of data is missing. To solve this issue, we removed all records before 2004 and kept only US companies. We removed more than half of the companies, resulting in 18,000 records. </p>
  <p>We found that though the company market was a great categorical dimension, it had more than 900 distinct values. We grouped them into 15 meta-markets that we later called sectors.</p>
  <p>We also had to clean up funding rounds. Each funding round could be categorized by type, such as "Seed" or "Series B"; but this sorting was not as sequential as we originally believed it to be. To solve this issue, we assigned a "funding round number" to the funding rounds of each company. This allowed us to group together all the first funding rounds, second funding rounds, and so on, and show the breakdown per funding type.</p>
</div>

<div class="section-title">
  <h2><span>Iterative Prototyping</span></h2>
  <p>Sketch, Test, Learn, Repeat</p>
</div>

<p class="centered-column">Following the User-Centered Design process, we created multiple prototypes that we tested. After each round of user testing, we improved the prototype.</p>

