  <div class="col-sm-8">
    <img src="/assets/images/projects/startupviz-sketch.jpg" class="img-responsive" alt="StartupViz sketching"/>
  </div>
  <div class="col-sm-4">
    <h3>Early sketches</h3>
    <p>We sketched different paper prototype versions to accomplish our goals, keeping in mind the data limitations. Given the data, we couldn’t represent everything, and we had to adapt the visualizations.</p>
    <p>For instance, we only had one principal quantitative value: the funding amounts. However, we had very good information about companies’ markets and regions.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
  <div class="col-sm-8">
    <img src="/assets/images/projects/startupviz-testing.jpg" class="img-responsive" alt="StartupViz user testing"/>
  </div>
  <div class="col-sm-4">
    <h3>User Testing</h3>
    <p>After sketching a few ideas, we wanted to find out if users preferred a particular layout before we started the process of creating a medium fidelity prototype. We asked five participants interested in startups to tell us what they liked about each layout. We also performed a card sorting activity to learn what users were most interested in.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
  <div class="col-sm-8">
    <img src="/assets/images/projects/startupviz-prototype.jpg" class="img-responsive" alt="StartupViz medium fidelity prototype"/>
  </div>
  <div class="col-sm-4">
    <h3>Medium Fidelity Prototype</h3>
    <p>After a few iterations, we created a click-through prototype. Using paper prototypes, we were limited in term of interactivity and the data presented was not relevant. It made very hard to get real feedback the information presented.</p>
    <p>We kept the original layout but we worked on individual graphs, selecting and presenting the information that was the most important (based on the card sort from user testing).</p>
  </div>
</div>

